# Outline Standards

Use these standards whenever creating, reviewing, or optimizing PPT outlines.

## Core Principles

- **Visual carries the story:** The composition communicates each slide's narrative, sequence, contrast, or transformation before any text is read.
- **Text earns its place:** Bullets act as labels, anchors, and reasoning the visual cannot show; cut anything the visual already conveys.
- **One slide, one idea:** Resolve every slide to a single explicit takeaway, not a collection of loosely related facts.
- **Built for live presentation:** Design for an audience scanning in seconds while the speaker talks, not for a reader studying a document.

## Required Structure

```markdown
# PPT Outline: [Presentation Title]

---

## Slide 1: [Slide Title]
- **Label:** Self-contained explanation that states why the point matters
- Core insight: Main takeaway that ties the slide together
[Visual: Main composition and focal object; layout direction; recurring motifs; style constraints; no watermark or fake logos]
[Speech: Conversational presenter narration for this slide]

---

## Appendix: Global Visual Requirements
- **Theme:** Colors, accents
- **Fonts:** Title/body fonts and sizes
```

- Start with `# PPT Outline: [Title]`.
- Separate the title, every slide, and the appendix with `---`.
- Use sequential slide headers: `## Slide N: [Title]`.
- End every slide with one `[Visual: ...]` tag and one `[Speech: ...]` tag.
- Include `## Appendix: Global Visual Requirements` after the final slide.

## Slide Categories

Use exactly these three slide categories:

- **Cover-Ending Slides:** Use for the opening title slide and final Q&A/thank-you slide. Keep bullets to 2-4 lines, make the premise or closing takeaway immediately legible, and visually reconnect the ending to the cover.
- **Transition Slides:** Use for objectives, section dividers, roadmaps, and major act changes. Repeat the full roadmap or section map, bold only the current section, and include a visual progress marker such as `progress bar N/total`.
- **Content Slides:** Use for teaching, concepts, workflows, case studies, comparisons, and conclusions. Teach one clear idea with 5-6 substantial bullets and an explicit takeaway such as `Core insight:`, `Core logic:`, or `Anti-pattern:`.

## Writing Standards

- Write self-contained bullets that make sense without relying on the slide title.
- Prefer `**Label:** explanation` bullets that explain why the point matters, not just what it is.
- Keep text supportive and compact so the slide is not forced to tell the whole story through bullets.
- Use summary bullets to make the takeaway explicit: `Core insight:`, `Core logic:`, or `Anti-pattern:`.
- Use tables for taxonomies or comparisons, and sub-bullets only for workflows such as `Plan -> Implement -> Test`.

```markdown
# Good
- **Clear Boundaries:** Each component should handle a single, focused responsibility
- Core insight: Systems perform best with clear interfaces and isolation

# Bad (too brief)
- Token limit: 128k-200k
- Performance: Fast
```

## Visual Tags

Write `[Visual:]` prompts as production-ready art direction that tells the slide's story faster than decoration or text alone.

- Specify the focal object, foreground/background structure, and layout pattern: split-screen, grid, pipeline, roadmap, or system diagram.
- Show the narrative visually through contrast, sequence, hierarchy, cause/effect, before/after, or movement through a workflow.
- Preserve deck continuity with recurring motifs such as beams, nodes, panels, icons, section colors, or progress markers.
- Keep generated-image text minimal; avoid dense labels, watermarks, fake logos, AI-generation stamps, and decorative text unless required.
- When reference slide images exist, extract concrete style rules from them and reuse those rules in later visual prompts.

## Speech Tags

Write `[Speech:]` as natural presenter narration.

- Expand on the bullets with context, emphasis, transitions, or examples not already visible on the slide.
- Aim for 60-90 seconds on content slides; use shorter scripts for cover, ending, and transition slides when appropriate.
- Keep the tone conversational, as if presenting live rather than reading a document.

## Appendix Requirements

The appendix defines reusable deck-wide constraints:

- **Theme:** Colors, background, accents
- **Fonts:** Title/body fonts and sizes
- **Layout:** Aspect ratio, spacing, split ratios
- **Animations:** Transition styles
- **Icons:** Icon set, size, color
- **Diagrams:** Shared diagram style rules
